SIMPLE: fade
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fade
<hw>Fade</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., prob. fr. L.
<ets>vapidus</ets> vapid, or possibly fr,<ets>fatuus</ets> foolish,
insipid.]</ety> <def>Weak; insipid; tasteless; commonplace.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Passages that are somewhat
<xex>fade</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jeffrey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His masculine taste gave him a sense of something <qex>fade</qex>
and ludicrous.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fade
<hw>Fade</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Faded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>faden</ets>,
<ets>vaden</ets>, prob. fr. <ets>fade</ets>, <pos>a.</pos>; cf. Prov. D.
<ets>vadden</ets> to fade, wither, <ets>vaddigh languid</ets>,
<ets>torpid</ets>. Cf. <er>Fade</er>, <pos>a.</pos>,
<er>Vade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become fade; to grow weak; to
lose strength; to decay; to perish gradually; to wither, as a
plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earth mourneth and <qex>fadeth</qex> away.</q> <rj><qau>Is.
xxiv. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lose freshness, color, or brightness; to become
faint in hue or tint; hence, to be wanting in color.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Flowers that never <xex>fade</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sink away; to disappear gradually; to grow dim;
to vanish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stars shall <qex>fade</qex> away.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He makes a swanlike end,⟦br⟧
<qex>Fading</qex> in music.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fade
<hw>Fade</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to wither; to deprive of
freshness or vigor; to wear away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No winter could his laurels <qex>fade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Faded</ent>⟦br⟧
